00:12:03.450 --> 00:12:13.260
to read any of those books and
what your life would be like,

00:12:13.260 --> 00:12:16.370
how much less rich it would be.

00:12:16.370 --> 00:12:31.140
In my own case, I came from
a family that was not college

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:33.560
or high school educated,
and the great pleasure

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:39.170
in my life was learning how
to read and learning the world

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:44.180
that was outside the
world that I grew up in,

00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:46.370
and I grew up in
Baltimore, and the head

00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:49.440
of the library is now -- which
is the library in Baltimore --

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:53.710
is now our Librarian
of Congress.

00:12:53.710 --> 00:12:55.430
[Applause] The first woman
and the first African American

00:12:55.430 --> 00:13:04.130
to be Librarian of Congress, and
also I think the first librarian

00:13:04.130 --> 00:13:07.670
to be Librarian of Congress

00:13:07.670 --> 00:13:11.430
in almost a century,
so congratulations.

00:13:11.430 --> 00:13:14.650
[Applause] Sadly, and it's hard
to believe, it is very hard

00:13:14.650 --> 00:13:18.360
to believe, but 45
million Americans,

00:13:18.360 --> 00:13:22.950
about 14% of our population
is functionally illiterate,

00:13:22.950 --> 00:13:26.960
which means they can't read
past a fourth grade level.

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:29.940
43 million Americans can't
read at all, stop sign,

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:32.460
they can't read at all.

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:40.100
This country purports to be
the wealthiest in the world,

00:13:40.100 --> 00:13:44.930
and in many ways we
complain about and think

00:13:44.930 --> 00:13:50.060
about the terrible problem
we have income inequality

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:52.600
and social mobility, it
goes back in my view to one

00:13:52.600 --> 00:13:56.540
of the major causes of literacy,
people's inability to read.

00:13:56.540 --> 00:13:59.420
If you cannot read,
you have limited chance

00:13:59.420 --> 00:14:00.950
of getting a very good job.

00:14:00.950 --> 00:14:12.530
Those people cannot functionally
read or read at all are going

00:14:12.530 --> 00:14:14.180
to make less than
two-thirds of what --

00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:19.710
a third of what somebody who can
read will make during the course

00:14:19.710 --> 00:14:27.260
of their lifetime.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:28.560
And that's sad.

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:31.310
Not only will they not get the
pleasure of reading and the joy

00:14:31.310 --> 00:14:32.850
of life you have from reading,

00:14:32.850 --> 00:14:34.910
but they're going
to earn a lot less.

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:37.790
In addition, you should
recognize that people

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:41.580
who cannot read have a much
greater chance of being

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:42.880
in our federal criminal system.

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:46.200
In fact, roughly
65% of the people

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:51.260
in our federal prisons are
functionally illiterate.

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:55.080
And roughly 80% of the people

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:58.860
in the juvenile delinquency
system are

00:14:58.860 --> 00:15:01.030
functionally illiterate.

00:15:01.030 --> 00:15:04.110
So if you cannot read,
you're not likely

00:15:04.110 --> 00:15:05.680
to make a good living.

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:07.600
You may well be in need
of public assistance.

00:15:07.600 --> 00:15:13.060
In fact, 80% of people
in public assistance is

00:15:13.060 --> 00:15:14.360
functionally illiterate.

00:15:14.360 --> 00:15:20.910
So this problem is not just
generation of adults I'm talking

00:15:20.910 --> 00:15:22.950
about but also for children.

00:15:22.950 --> 00:15:28.420
Because as we all know, the best
way to teach a child to read is

00:15:28.420 --> 00:15:32.070
by parental reading to them.

00:15:32.070 --> 00:15:34.250
But if you can't
read as a parent,

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:36.350
how can you read
to your children?

00:15:36.350 --> 00:15:40.470
So what happens very
often is the children --

00:15:40.470 --> 00:15:42.090
the children of parents
who cannot read,

00:15:42.090 --> 00:15:43.390
they don't learn how to read.

00:15:43.390 --> 00:15:45.400
Therefore when the time comes
to measure them in third

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:46.880
or fourth grade they
fall way behind.

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:50.220
The children of parents
who cannot read had

00:15:50.220 --> 00:15:53.200
about a 20% chance
of being able to get

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:57.830
through the fourth grade
proficiency levels.

00:15:57.830 --> 00:16:00.310
And if you can't read at
the fourth grade level

00:16:00.310 --> 00:16:02.800
by the time you're in the
fourth grade, in other words,

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:05.400
you're not really
reading proficient,

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:07.600
you have a much greater chance
of being a high school dropout.

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:10.370
In fact, 75% of the people drop

00:16:10.370 --> 00:16:13.370
out of high school are
functionally illiterate,

00:16:13.370 --> 00:16:14.670
and by the time they're

00:16:14.670 --> 00:16:16.990
in the fourth grade they
were already really behind.

00:16:16.990 --> 00:16:21.980
There's no one thing we can
do to solve the problem.

00:16:21.980 --> 00:16:27.700
The Literacy Awards are
designed to get attention to it.

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:29.630
As Doris Kearns Goodwin
would say,

00:16:29.630 --> 00:16:33.170
"the world will no
longer remember what we do

00:16:33.170 --> 00:16:34.470
here tonight.

00:16:34.470 --> 00:16:36.320
" And the awards are
relatively modest.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:41.240
It's my goal to get
attention and the Library

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:45.650
of Congress being involved,
doing all the hard work,

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:49.890
they make it more important than
it would be if I was doing it

00:16:49.890 --> 00:16:52.470
by myself, so I thank
the Library

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:54.870
of Congress for doing this.

00:16:54.870 --> 00:17:00.290
Everybody involved in literacy
organizations deserves the

00:17:00.290 --> 00:17:04.100
credit for actually helping
to solve this problem

00:17:04.100 --> 00:17:07.200
and deal with this problem.

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:12.430
But this problem is
much bigger than anybody

00:17:12.430 --> 00:17:15.750
in this room can solve.

00:17:15.750 --> 00:17:22.460
We much more federal resources
and public attention and we need

00:17:22.460 --> 00:17:29.440
to recognize that if we're
ever going to solve the income

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:34.360
and equality problem and
social mobility problem

00:17:34.360 --> 00:17:40.580
of this country we have to begin
by teaching young children how

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:43.340
to read and enjoy reading.

00:17:43.340 --> 00:17:50.370
All of you would probably say
that if you didn't know how

00:17:50.370 --> 00:17:56.150
to read your life would be less
fulfilling, that's for sure.

00:17:56.150 --> 00:18:03.330
You might have less money,
but less fulfilling a life.

00:18:03.330 --> 00:18:06.380
I just want you to
think tonight as you go

00:18:06.380 --> 00:18:09.800
