It's quick.

00:37:39.630 --> 00:37:41.930
I have a ten-year-old
son, Jackson Leroy

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:44.020
and I have a 16-year-old
daughter.

00:37:44.020 --> 00:37:48.480
When my son was four years old
we realized he needed glasses.

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:53.740
And when he was about
seven we realized

00:37:53.740 --> 00:37:57.690
that he was reading
differently from other people.

00:37:57.690 --> 00:38:02.410
And then we got him tested and
we found out that he had a lot

00:38:02.410 --> 00:38:03.780
of reading differences.

00:38:03.780 --> 00:38:10.510
And that he was having a lot
of stress about how he --

00:38:10.510 --> 00:38:11.830
knowing he was reading
different.

00:38:11.830 --> 00:38:13.890
And I know there are a
lot of people in the room

00:38:13.890 --> 00:38:18.310
who have encountered the young
people who read differently.

00:38:18.310 --> 00:38:23.230
And about two months ago we had
our 16-year-old daughter tested.

00:38:23.230 --> 00:38:27.960
I should stop and tell you,
my partner is Jew let Woodall,

00:38:27.960 --> 00:38:32.860
the most wonderful
person in the world

00:38:32.860 --> 00:38:35.680
and does just world-changing
work.

00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:38.500
And because we're two women,
we can decide who gets

00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:40.550
to have what kid when.

00:38:40.550 --> 00:38:43.210
So I gave birth to my daughter

00:38:43.210 --> 00:38:46.030
and my partner gave
birth to our son Jackson.

00:38:46.030 --> 00:38:50.780
We have these two amazing
kids and love them very much,

00:38:50.780 --> 00:38:54.080
and when they get on our nerves,
I get to go off as ambassador,

00:38:54.080 --> 00:38:55.870
gets to go to the clinic.

00:38:55.870 --> 00:39:01.600
But I read differently
as a young person.

00:39:01.600 --> 00:39:05.210
I knew that I would have
been diagnosed as dyslexic

00:39:05.210 --> 00:39:07.870
in this day and age, but I
grew up in a neighborhood

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:10.670
where parents weren't
spending lots of money

00:39:10.670 --> 00:39:13.850
to get psych socials done
to see what was going

00:39:13.850 --> 00:39:16.290
on with kids' reading.

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:19.080
We did that and got our
kids tested and turned

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:21.740
out both had reading
differences,

00:39:21.740 --> 00:39:25.560
and that there's a
whole industry out there

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:30.980
where you can pay lots of
money to get your kids on par,

00:39:30.980 --> 00:39:34.250
up to level, and there
are a lot of people

00:39:34.250 --> 00:39:35.550
that don't have that money.

00:39:35.550 --> 00:39:38.220
Not only do they not
have the money to find

00:39:38.220 --> 00:39:40.460
out what their young
people are struggling with,

00:39:40.460 --> 00:39:41.760
but they don't have the money

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:44.610
to then help them get
through the struggle.

00:39:44.610 --> 00:39:47.070
And there's so many
places where --

00:39:47.070 --> 00:39:49.200
so many schools where
they don't have the tools

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:51.510
to help the young people
with those struggles.

00:39:51.510 --> 00:39:53.390
And it's hard.

00:39:53.390 --> 00:39:56.110
And it's hard for me
as a mom to figure

00:39:56.110 --> 00:40:00.440
out what the playing field is
I'm choosing for my young people

00:40:00.440 --> 00:40:03.550
and it's hard for me
as ambassador to go

00:40:03.550 --> 00:40:06.820
around the country and see
how many young people are

00:40:06.820 --> 00:40:10.370
struggling, either because
they don't have access to books

00:40:10.370 --> 00:40:16.160
in their homes, because their
parents haven't had the tools

00:40:16.160 --> 00:40:18.600
to learn to read so that
they could then go and read

00:40:18.600 --> 00:40:22.950
to the young people, or because
they're undiagnosed in some way.

00:40:22.950 --> 00:40:25.680
And I think as writers,
as readers,

00:40:25.680 --> 00:40:29.440
as people who have means,
as people who have access,

00:40:29.440 --> 00:40:31.100
we can change the world.

00:40:31.100 --> 00:40:35.680
We can change this narrative
and we can end the school

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:37.710
to prison pipeline
that is coming

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:39.470
out of what Mr. Rubenstein said,

00:40:39.470 --> 00:40:45.210
about kids who are weak
readers becoming the people

00:40:45.210 --> 00:40:48.090
who are feeding the
prison industrial complex.

00:40:48.090 --> 00:40:56.070
So, I want to thank the universe
for giving me the gift to write.

00:40:56.070 --> 00:40:58.580
I want to thank the
writers who came before me.

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:01.860
I know we all have writers who
came before us who taught us,

00:41:01.860 --> 00:41:04.240
James Baldwin and Audrey
Lord and so many more.

00:41:04.240 --> 00:41:07.250
I want to thank the
Library of Congress

00:41:07.250 --> 00:41:08.890
for giving us this space

00:41:08.890 --> 00:41:11.580
to actually have
these conversations

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:15.270
about what it means to
create readers and learners

00:41:15.270 --> 00:41:18.570
and thinkers, and I want to
thank you for really thinking

00:41:18.570 --> 00:41:21.710
about giving all the money to --

00:41:21.710 --> 00:41:25.340
you don't have to
give all of it.

00:41:25.340 --> 00:41:28.720
You can give the royalties
of a part of one book.

00:41:28.720 --> 00:41:32.030
You can give the royalties
of all of one book.

00:41:32.030 --> 00:41:34.680
You know, there are
ways to do this.

00:41:34.680 --> 00:41:37.810
I was watching Aretha's
funeral all day long.

00:41:37.810 --> 00:41:40.310
It was on all day long.

00:41:40.310 --> 00:41:41.780
And it was amazing.

00:41:41.780 --> 00:41:44.300
But I thought about
tithing in the black church

00:41:44.300 --> 00:41:46.520
and in many churches
you tithe, right?

00:41:46.520 --> 00:41:49.690
You give a percentage of
your income toward some kind

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:50.990
of greater good.

00:41:50.990 --> 00:41:52.710
And this is a greater
good we need

00:41:52.710 --> 00:41:55.810
to put our finances
into right now.

00:41:55.810 --> 00:41:57.230
This is going to
change the world.

00:41:57.230 --> 00:42:01.280
This is going to level
the playing field,

00:42:01.280 --> 00:42:05.930
if we're not thinking about
doing it for the adults,

00:42:05.930 --> 00:42:22.010
Let's do it for the
young people.

00:42:22.010 --> 00:42:33.200
So that's all I've got to say.

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:34.500
Thank you.

00:42:34.500 --> 00:42:35.800
[Applause] Announcer:
Ladies and gentlemen,

00:42:35.800 --> 00:42:37.220
please welcome Jon Meacham.

00:42:37.220 --> 00:42:39.550
[Applause] J. Meacham: Okay,
ambassador Woodson got a medal,

00:42:39.550 --> 00:42:42.130
Brian writes better
than Rowling...

00:42:42.130 --> 00:42:43.770
thank y'all for coming.

00:42:43.770 --> 00:42:47.810
This may be the most significant
gathering of talent and skill

00:42:47.810 --> 00:42:50.770
and literary ability in one room

00:42:50.770 --> 00:42:54.810
since Doris Kearns
Goodwin dined alone.

00:42:54.810 --> 00:42:59.010
Thank you for having me.

00:42:59.010 --> 00:43:00.830
I love the National
Book Festival

00:43:00.830 --> 00:43:06.010
because of its humbling
function for me.

00:43:06.010 --> 00:43:10.150
Ten years ago I was here, and
I was on my way to give my talk

00:43:10.150 --> 00:43:11.870
at that point about
Andrew Jackson.

00:43:11.870 --> 00:43:17.690
And a woman ran up to me,
which doesn't happen enough.

00:43:17.690 --> 00:43:18.990
[ Laughter ]

00:43:18.990 --> 00:43:20.800
Or ever. Because if they
would, they would have to get

00:43:20.800 --> 00:43:23.200
out of their medical device
if they wanted to see me.

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:26.500
And she said "oh,
my God, it's you!

00:43:26.500 --> 00:43:28.490
." I said, yes.

00:43:28.490 --> 00:43:33.070
Existentially speaking,
that's hard to argue with.

00:43:33.070 --> 00:43:35.810
She said I admire your work
so much, your books have meant

00:43:35.810 --> 00:43:37.290
so much to me and my family.

00:43:37.290 --> 00:43:39.840
Will you wait right
here and I want

00:43:39.840 --> 00:43:41.610
to get your new book
and have you sign it.

00:43:41.610 --> 00:43:42.910
I said, yes, ma'am.

00:43:42.910 --> 00:43:44.210
I was standing there thinking,

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:45.950
this is the way the
world is supposed to be.

00:43:45.950 --> 00:43:49.360
Women are supposed to admire
you and you to sign their books.

00:43:49.360 --> 00:43:50.720
This was perfect.

00:43:50.720 --> 00:43:55.850
She brought back John
Grisham's latest novel.

00:43:56.930 --> 00:43:58.230
It gets worse.

00:43:58.230 --> 00:44:00.890
At that point I was
writing a biography

00:44:00.890 --> 00:44:02.700
of George Herbert Walker Bush.

00:44:02.700 --> 00:44:04.120
It was a Saturday.

00:44:04.120 --> 00:44:06.610
I went to Kennebunkport
the next day.

00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:10.310
I was at lunch with the
Bushes anded to this story,

00:44:10.310 --> 00:44:15.760
expecting some motherly
reassurance from Mrs. Bush.

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:18.090
She looked across
the table and said,

00:44:18.090 --> 00:44:20.200
how do you think Mr.
John Grisham would feel?

00:44:20.200 --> 00:44:28.880
He's a very handsome man.

00:44:28.880 --> 00:44:30.180
[ Laughter ]

00:44:30.180 --> 00:44:33.100
And you put me after these
two, so I'm never coming back.

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:35.080
Thank you all very much.

00:44:35.080 --> 00:44:38.550
No, I'm delighted to be
here, honored to be here.

00:44:38.550 --> 00:44:42.110
I'm going to tell you a
story about why I write

00:44:42.110 --> 00:44:46.380
about what I write, and it
has to do with both the past

00:44:46.380 --> 00:44:47.910
and the future for me.

00:44:47.910 --> 00:44:50.580
And I think that ultimately
that's the significance

00:44:50.580 --> 00:44:54.840
of history, it is our past
but I firmly believe as much

00:44:54.840 --> 00:44:58.540
as I believe anything that
it is absolutely essential

00:44:58.540 --> 00:45:02.040
to shaping the present
and the future.

00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:04.930
I you up on missionary ridge,
a Civil War battlefield

00:45:04.930 --> 00:45:06.750
in Chattanooga, Tennessee.

00:45:06.750 --> 00:45:12.600
It was the place where
Braxton Bragg lost to Grant,

00:45:12.600 --> 00:45:14.960
how Sherman got to Georgia.

00:45:14.960 --> 00:45:18.950
Some of my friends in
Atlanta never came to visit.

00:45:18.950 --> 00:45:20.250
I'll wait.

00:45:20.250 --> 00:45:22.310
It's kind of funny...

00:45:22.310 --> 00:45:25.830
You get further north and you
have to let that simmer a bit.

00:45:25.830 --> 00:45:32.350
I grew up 600 yards from
Bragg's headquarters,

00:45:32.350 --> 00:45:33.890
where the line was broken,

00:45:33.890 --> 00:45:36.780
Douglas McArthur's
father won the medal

00:45:36.780 --> 00:45:39.240
of honor at the age of 17.

00:45:39.240 --> 00:45:43.160
Two miles down the road the
other way was Chief John Ross'

00:45:43.160 --> 00:45:46.220
house, the head of
the Cherokee nation.

00:45:46.220 --> 00:45:49.480
The Cherokee tribe which
did more than any other

00:45:49.480 --> 00:45:55.640
to meet the demands of a
white majoritarian authority,

00:45:55.640 --> 00:45:59.800
and yet still found itself
fundamentally betrayed

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:02.500
by that country.

00:46:02.500 --> 00:46:09.330
There for me I could find balls
in the yard where I grew up.

00:46:09.330 --> 00:46:11.150
History was a tactile thing.

00:46:11.150 --> 00:46:15.020
And it was also incredibly
complex,

00:46:15.020 --> 00:46:17.830
because there were
two living monuments,

00:46:17.830 --> 00:46:21.930
two of the great original
sins of American life.

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:26.040
African American slavery
and Native American removal.

00:46:26.040 --> 00:46:29.120
And yet the house
in which I grew up,

00:46:29.120 --> 00:46:31.970
the house between
those two places was my

00:46:31.970 --> 00:46:34.160
grandfather's house.

00:46:34.160 --> 00:46:38.050
He was born in 1913
on June 22nd,

00:46:38.050 --> 00:46:41.690
1941 as a practicing
lawyer he decided

00:46:41.690 --> 00:46:43.360
to join the United States Navy

00:46:43.360 --> 00:46:46.820
because Hitler had just
invaded the Soviet Union.

00:46:46.820 --> 00:46:49.710
My grandfather believed at
that point war was inevitable,

00:46:49.710 --> 00:46:53.410
global war, and he wanted
to be first in line.

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:56.250
And spent four years
in the Pacific.

00:46:56.250 --> 00:46:58.910
I'm one of those people
who would not be here

00:46:58.910 --> 00:47:03.240
if Harry Truman had not made the
decision he made in late July

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:06.730
and August of 1945, because my
grandfather was set to be part

00:47:06.730 --> 00:47:09.130
of the invasion of
the home islands

00:47:09.130 --> 00:47:12.410
with unimaginable
casualty figures.

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:15.110
Again, complexity.

00:47:15.110 --> 00:47:16.720
The general and the universal,

00:47:16.720 --> 00:47:21.150
but with a discernible,
personal impact.

00:47:21.150 --> 00:47:26.110
I believe that I was drawn
to history and to biography

00:47:26.110 --> 00:47:29.850
because I grew up not in a land

00:47:29.850 --> 00:47:33.610
of where there were absolute
moral certitudes of black

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:38.630
and white and good and evil,
but a kind of ambiguity.

00:47:38.630 --> 00:47:42.150
And I was taught
because of the heroism

00:47:42.150 --> 00:47:46.660
of that man whose house sat
between these two emblems

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:50.050
of our falling short, that
the important thing was

00:47:50.050 --> 00:47:52.150
to stay in the fight.

00:47:52.150 --> 00:47:54.710
Because the United States,
had it not been founded,

00:47:54.710 --> 00:47:57.450
had we not come through
the cataclysm of the war,

00:47:57.450 --> 00:48:00.880
had we not continued the
journey and the search,

00:48:00.880 --> 00:48:04.400
not for a perfect union
but for a more perfect one,

00:48:04.400 --> 00:48:07.070
we would never have been
able to project the force

00:48:07.070 --> 00:48:11.110
across the seas to defeat
tyranny at Mid century

00:48:11.110 --> 00:48:15.370
in the second world war.

00:48:15.370 --> 00:48:19.540
And so between these two
sins stood a man I revered,

00:48:19.540 --> 00:48:21.370
who was not perfect.

00:48:21.370 --> 00:48:23.380
But who did the right
thing and put his life

00:48:23.380 --> 00:48:26.260
on the line for others.

00:48:26.260 --> 00:48:32.240
In that moral universe, in the
contradictory nature of that,

00:48:32.240 --> 00:48:36.780
I began to see that the
human story was, in fact,

00:48:36.780 --> 00:48:40.360
the most representative
one, the most enduring one.

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:45.580
And I think we learn most from
the past, not when we look

00:48:45.580 --> 00:48:50.110
down on it condescendingly
or up at it adoringly,

00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:52.600
but when we look
at it in the eye.

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:57.240
Take it for what it was and
realize that the damn miracle

00:48:57.240 --> 00:49:01.390
of the United States is that
we've gotten this much right.

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:05.740
We live in a fallen
sinful world,

00:49:05.740 --> 00:49:07.800
the founders understood it.

00:49:07.800 --> 00:49:09.390
The constitution is one

00:49:09.390 --> 00:49:11.950
of the most Calvinistic
documents you can imagine.

00:49:11.950 --> 00:49:16.200
It assumes we're driven
by appetite and ambition.

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:19.800
It assumes that we're mostly
going to do the wrong thing.

00:49:19.800 --> 00:49:23.350
And they were right.

00:49:23.350 --> 00:49:25.670
But what did it give us?

00:49:25.670 --> 00:49:31.540
It gave us the means by which
to seek our better angels.

00:49:31.540 --> 00:49:33.720
And I don't know about
you all, but in the course

00:49:33.720 --> 00:49:39.010
of a given day, if I get
things right 51% of the time,

00:49:39.010 --> 00:49:41.110
that's a helluva good day.

00:49:41.110 --> 00:49:45.550
And I think that's true in
the lives of nations as well.

00:49:45.550 --> 00:49:48.800
I've written about
very complicated men

00:49:48.800 --> 00:49:51.810
and women, mostly men.

00:49:51.810 --> 00:49:55.380
I've written about them because
-- not because they were perfect

00:49:55.380 --> 00:49:58.020
but because they
were so imperfect and

00:49:58.020 --> 00:50:01.140
yet at critical moments
rose to the occasion

00:50:01.140 --> 00:50:06.440
and pushed us forward, pushed us
toward that more perfect union.

00:50:06.440 --> 00:50:09.890
I've read about Thomas
Jefferson, a slave owner

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:13.310
who nevertheless wrote the most
important sentence ever written

00:50:13.310 --> 00:50:16.510
in the English language as
our friend David likes to say.

00:50:16.510 --> 00:50:18.350
That all men are created equal.

00:50:18.350 --> 00:50:20.320
I get nervous when
I hear David say

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:22.350
that about the most
important sentence written

00:50:22.350 --> 00:50:25.270
in the English language because
the phrase reminds me of a story

00:50:25.270 --> 00:50:29.000
about the Texas school board
candidate who was running

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:32.200
and was against Spanish being
taught and went on the stump

00:50:32.200 --> 00:50:34.010
and said "If English
was good enough

00:50:34.010 --> 00:50:40.000
for our lord Jesus Christ,
it's good enough for Texas."

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:41.520
As a Tennessean, we have

00:50:41.520 --> 00:50:44.980
to remind Texans they
would still be part

00:50:44.980 --> 00:50:47.110
of Spain if it weren't for us.

00:50:47.110 --> 00:50:50.290
I made that joke once to
Governor George W. Bush

00:50:50.290 --> 00:50:53.380
and he said, "heh,
that's funny asshole."

00:50:58.180 --> 00:51:01.640
The miracle of the country is

00:51:01.640 --> 00:51:05.730
that despite our flaws,
we stay in the fight.

00:51:05.730 --> 00:51:07.840
We get things right.

00:51:07.840 --> 00:51:09.140
A final story about...

00:51:09.140 --> 00:51:11.450
another man I wrote
about, Andrew Jackson,

00:51:11.450 --> 00:51:14.680
who saved the union in
1832, Franklin Roosevelt

00:51:14.680 --> 00:51:16.980
who saved democracy,
saved capitalism

00:51:16.980 --> 00:51:22.580
and signed executive order
9906, Japanese Americans.

00:51:22.580 --> 00:51:26.530
George Herbert Walker Bush who
got a lot wrong in his life,

00:51:26.530 --> 00:51:30.780
imperfect man but he did leave
us with a more perfect union.

00:51:30.780 --> 00:51:32.870
I'll leave you with this.

00:51:32.870 --> 00:51:37.630
About a year ago, the incumbent
president -- Voldemort --

00:51:37.630 --> 00:51:50.760
[Applause] -- was on his way
to Nashville where I live

00:51:50.760 --> 00:51:54.930
to give -- to lay a wreath at
the tomb of Andrew Jackson.

00:51:54.930 --> 00:51:56.530
I live in Nashville.

00:51:56.530 --> 00:51:58.830
And he was coming down
and I thought, well,

00:51:58.830 --> 00:52:00.130
I should do something.

00:52:00.130 --> 00:52:03.400
And so I wrote an open letter
to the president that said

00:52:03.400 --> 00:52:05.020
"If you're going to
embrace Andrew Jackson,

00:52:05.020 --> 00:52:07.240
don't just embrace
the crazy parts."

00:52:07.240 --> 00:52:11.340
There are plenty of
crazy parts to embrace.

00:52:11.340 --> 00:52:15.500
He once said only two regrets in
life were he had not shot Clay

00:52:15.500 --> 00:52:20.290
and hung Calhoun, his
own vice president.

00:52:20.290 --> 00:52:21.860
We now know no one felt that way

00:52:21.860 --> 00:52:24.900
about their running
mate until John McCain.

00:52:30.480 --> 00:52:34.450
But -- Senator McCain liked
that joke, I can report.

00:52:34.450 --> 00:52:37.440
I cleared it with
him some years ago.

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:42.780
I said, if you're going to
embrace Jackson, he was,

00:52:42.780 --> 00:52:45.580
for all his faults, someone who
believed in the American union.

00:52:45.580 --> 00:52:47.600
He was devoted to the
constitutional experiment

00:52:47.600 --> 00:52:50.590
as flawed as it was, kept
us together through crises,

00:52:50.590 --> 00:52:53.350
and was a great negotiator
and understood weaknesses

00:52:53.350 --> 00:52:56.120
and knew how to use them.

00:52:56.120 --> 00:52:58.870
I wrote an open letter on
the front page of the paper,

00:52:58.870 --> 00:53:00.450
only thing that greeted
the president

00:53:00.450 --> 00:53:01.870
when he came to Nashville.

00:53:01.870 --> 00:53:06.600
Had no effect whatsoever.

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:08.970
The next day, true
story, my phone rang,

00:53:08.970 --> 00:53:14.470
my most recent subject, George
H.W. Bush in the hospital a lot

00:53:14.470 --> 00:53:16.980
that winter and his staff was
giving him things to read.

00:53:16.980 --> 00:53:19.260
He read this.

00:53:19.260 --> 00:53:21.750
Get Meacham on the phone.

00:53:21.750 --> 00:53:23.720
The key to doing his voice,

00:53:23.720 --> 00:53:28.730
as Dana carver said is Mr.
Rogers trying to be John Wayne.

00:53:28.730 --> 00:53:31.620
How ya doing?

00:53:31.620 --> 00:53:34.040
I'm fine, Mr. President.

00:53:34.040 --> 00:53:37.020
He said, I read your
letter to Jackson.

00:53:37.020 --> 00:53:39.270
I thought, oh, the
ole boy is losing it.

00:53:39.270 --> 00:53:41.570
He thinks I'm writing
letters to dead people.

00:53:41.570 --> 00:53:43.930
I said, thank you.

00:53:43.930 --> 00:53:48.140
Actually, it was a letter
to Trump, not Jackson.

00:53:48.140 --> 00:53:51.760
He said, yeah, but Jackson
will pay more attention.

00:54:18.050 --> 00:54:20.890
[Applause] Announcer:
Ladies and gentlemen,

00:54:20.890 --> 00:54:23.730
please welcome Amy Tan.

00:54:23.730 --> 00:54:35.470
[Applause] A. Tan: I've been
sitting here thinking what

00:54:35.470 --> 00:54:40.350
excuse I could come up with
to say why I'm not prepared.

00:54:40.350 --> 00:54:41.650
I had deadlines.

00:54:41.650 --> 00:54:42.950
They had three hours of sleep.

00:54:42.950 --> 00:54:46.600
I was on an airplane before I
said, I really do have to think

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:48.330
about the fact I'm
going to be talking

00:54:48.330 --> 00:54:50.130
in front of Annie Proulx.

00:54:50.130 --> 00:54:54.640
I want to tell you a story about
reading, and that is my debt

00:54:54.640 --> 00:54:56.240
of gratitude to the libraries

00:54:56.240 --> 00:54:58.260
from the time I was
a young child.

00:54:58.260 --> 00:55:02.060
I was from an immigrant,
a frugal immigrant family,

00:55:02.060 --> 00:55:05.060
in fact, an illegal
immigrant family.

00:55:05.060 --> 00:55:06.950
We didn't have a lot
of money for books.

00:55:06.950 --> 00:55:08.550
We didn't have books
in the house.

00:55:08.550 --> 00:55:11.700
By the time I was six years
old I would walk to the library

00:55:11.700 --> 00:55:15.470
by myself and carry as many
books as I could home to read.

00:55:15.470 --> 00:55:18.930
Now, I didn't learn how to read
before that because the powers

00:55:18.930 --> 00:55:24.390
that be in the 1950s deemed
it irresponsible of parents

00:55:24.390 --> 00:55:26.320
to teach their children
how to read,

00:55:26.320 --> 00:55:29.880
because they would probably
do it by really dumb methods,

00:55:29.880 --> 00:55:33.480
and their children would end up
with learning problems the rest

00:55:33.480 --> 00:55:35.920
of their lives, probably
be chronic bed wetters

00:55:35.920 --> 00:55:38.230
and criminals and
all kinds of things.

00:55:38.230 --> 00:55:40.630
So parents just didn't do that.

00:55:40.630 --> 00:55:43.020
Hence no books in our house.

00:55:43.020 --> 00:55:46.380
I remember, though, in the
first grade there was a woman

00:55:46.380 --> 00:55:50.050
who confirmed this, that you
shouldn't teach your children

00:55:50.050 --> 00:55:51.390
to read early on.

00:55:51.390 --> 00:55:52.690
She came and she pulled me

00:55:52.690 --> 00:55:55.120
out of the classroom
and gave me a test.

00:55:55.120 --> 00:55:58.980
And later on she had -- did
an interview with my parents.

00:55:58.980 --> 00:56:01.320
I remember seeing
her, this young woman,

00:56:01.320 --> 00:56:03.540
sitting in the living room.

00:56:03.540 --> 00:56:06.830
And at the end of this,
my parents called me in

00:56:06.830 --> 00:56:08.450
and they told me the good news.

00:56:08.450 --> 00:56:13.200
They said that the woman had
done this test and she told them

00:56:13.200 --> 00:56:16.590
that I had what it would
take to be a doctor.

00:56:16.590 --> 00:56:22.590
This is like heroine
to a Chinese parent.

00:56:22.590 --> 00:56:26.640
So not only was I going to be a
concert pianist, it was already

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:29.060
in the works, I was
going to be a doctor.

00:56:29.060 --> 00:56:32.550
They told me also my English
skills were not that great,

00:56:32.550 --> 00:56:35.740
but doctors and pianists,
they really did not need

00:56:35.740 --> 00:56:38.280
to have that, it
wasn't a problem.

00:56:38.280 --> 00:56:41.880
The woman came twice a
year, gave me these tests.

00:56:41.880 --> 00:56:46.730
And the test became longer and
longer and I could never finish.

00:56:46.730 --> 00:56:48.870
I thought I was becoming
dumber and dumber,

00:56:48.870 --> 00:56:51.030
maybe she was wrong
about the first test.

00:56:51.030 --> 00:56:52.710
I wasn't inspired
enough to be a doctor,

00:56:52.710 --> 00:56:55.580
but I had to keep
up the pre-tests.

00:56:55.580 --> 00:56:59.830
My self-esteem was
based on those tests.

00:56:59.830 --> 00:57:03.110
I felt I was not
adequate to the task

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:05.810
of fulfilling my
immigrant parents' dreams.

00:57:05.810 --> 00:57:07.400
But I had a secret dream myself

00:57:07.400 --> 00:57:08.730
and that was to become
an artist.

00:57:08.730 --> 00:57:10.370
I love to draw.

00:57:10.370 --> 00:57:14.910
But that dream kind of
went north when my teacher,

00:57:14.910 --> 00:57:19.080
my art teacher, when I was
16, wrote in my report card

00:57:19.080 --> 00:57:22.590
that I had no imagination,
which was necessary

00:57:22.590 --> 00:57:26.170
to a deeper level of creativity.

00:57:26.170 --> 00:57:28.770
Okay... so out the
window goes that.

00:57:28.770 --> 00:57:35.780
At about the same time I got
my SAT scores and I scored

00:57:35.780 --> 00:57:38.770
in the 400s in English.

00:57:38.770 --> 00:57:42.420
Not really encouraging for
somebody who might want

00:57:42.420 --> 00:57:48.230
to make their living out of the
artful arrangement of words.

00:57:48.230 --> 00:57:51.960
Around that time my father and
brother died of brain tumors.

00:57:51.960 --> 00:57:54.780
Fortunately I became a
very rebellious girl.

00:57:54.780 --> 00:57:58.790
So, a year into being
a pre-med major,

00:57:58.790 --> 00:58:01.610
I quit and I became
an English major,

00:58:01.610 --> 00:58:03.660
much to the horror of my mother.

00:58:03.660 --> 00:58:06.680
But I love to read.

00:58:06.680 --> 00:58:08.540
I finished that major
in about three years

00:58:08.540 --> 00:58:11.650
and I became a linguistics
major and got a graduate degree

00:58:11.650 --> 00:58:14.240
in that because I love words.

00:58:14.240 --> 00:58:16.380
I love the feel, the texture,

00:58:16.380 --> 00:58:21.120
all the different ways
you could interpret words.

00:58:21.120 --> 00:58:24.370
I eventually became a
writer, business writer.

00:58:24.370 --> 00:58:27.070
I wrote things like direct mail,
the things you get in the mail

00:58:27.070 --> 00:58:31.540
that says "act now
and you get 20% off."

00:58:31.540 --> 00:58:33.090
Very good at that.

00:58:33.090 --> 00:58:36.200
I wrote business articles,
telecommunications.

00:58:36.200 --> 00:58:37.500
I hated it.

00:58:37.500 --> 00:58:42.200
And it wasn't until I was
33 years old, 33 years ago,

00:58:42.200 --> 00:58:44.450
that I started writing fiction.

00:58:44.450 --> 00:58:46.570
And fast forward.

00:58:46.570 --> 00:58:52.150
A few years ago I was trying to
write -- finish my latest book,

00:58:52.150 --> 00:58:53.620
which people call a memoir.

00:58:53.620 --> 00:58:59.140
It's really my imaginings
about why I became a writer.

00:58:59.140 --> 00:59:01.500
And I wondered about that test.

00:59:01.500 --> 00:59:03.150
What was the test really about?

00:59:03.150 --> 00:59:06.090
Because no professional would
have been so irresponsible

00:59:06.090 --> 00:59:09.140
to tell parents that
their child was going

00:59:09.140 --> 00:59:12.490
to be a doctor based
on one set of scores.

00:59:12.490 --> 00:59:14.810
So I did a Google
search and I put

00:59:14.810 --> 00:59:18.800
in 1958 first grade
Oakland School District,

00:59:18.800 --> 00:59:20.600
IQ Longitudinal.

00:59:20.600 --> 00:59:23.850
And the first thing that
came up was an article

00:59:23.850 --> 00:59:26.550
by a woman named
Dr. Delores Durkin.

00:59:26.550 --> 00:59:30.400
I thought, that was
the name of the woman.

00:59:30.400 --> 00:59:34.240
And it was a landmark
study she had done.

00:59:34.240 --> 00:59:37.150
It involved 49 children.

00:59:37.150 --> 00:59:43.700
Out of 5,003 first graders that
year, 49 of them were identified

00:59:43.700 --> 00:59:47.530
as having been illegally
taught to read.

00:59:47.530 --> 00:59:49.190
I was one of those readers.

00:59:49.190 --> 00:59:56.140
[Applause] Now, I
found that article.

00:59:56.140 --> 00:59:57.870
Not only did I find the article

00:59:57.870 --> 01:00:01.150
but through detective
work I found the book.

01:00:01.150 --> 01:00:03.480
You have to imagine my
reading this thing is

01:00:03.480 --> 01:00:06.540
like my self-esteem
was based on this test.

01:00:06.540 --> 01:00:10.510
I wasn't supposed
to be a doctor.

01:00:10.510 --> 01:00:12.340
I felt so betrayed.

01:00:12.340 --> 01:00:15.840
And I read this book and I had
all the charts and the layouts

01:00:15.840 --> 01:00:19.970
of facts and figures,
the Oriental kid.

01:00:19.970 --> 01:00:22.340
And there were five interviews.

01:00:22.340 --> 01:00:24.860
And I looked at them and
first I didn't recognize them

01:00:24.860 --> 01:00:27.930
because the names were math.

01:00:27.930 --> 01:00:31.160
And my mother said, I learn
you cannot teach children

01:00:31.160 --> 01:00:33.110
to enjoy music.

01:00:33.110 --> 01:00:34.410
I thought...

01:00:34.410 --> 01:00:35.710
that's my mother.

01:00:35.710 --> 01:00:39.920
I started reading and I
found out that my parents,

01:00:39.920 --> 01:00:44.250
they kept debating the question
that this woman, Dr. Durkin had,

01:00:44.250 --> 01:00:47.130
which was how did
she learn to read.

01:00:47.130 --> 01:00:49.980
My parents said, her
older brother, Peter,

01:00:49.980 --> 01:00:52.800
he's so brilliant, he
didn't learn to read,

01:00:52.800 --> 01:00:56.610
he waited until first grade,
and he skipped a grade

01:00:56.610 --> 01:00:58.350
because he just learned so fast.

01:00:58.350 --> 01:01:00.260
We followed the rules.

01:01:00.260 --> 01:01:03.280
And finally they kind
of admitted, well,

01:01:03.280 --> 01:01:06.380
I might have picked
it up from my brother,

01:01:06.380 --> 01:01:10.370
who was teaching my cousins,
our cousins from China to read.

01:01:10.370 --> 01:01:12.170
They didn't speak any English.

01:01:12.170 --> 01:01:15.880
And I had sat in on
these little lessons.

01:01:15.880 --> 01:01:18.690
And the others that my brother
brought home his textbooks

01:01:18.690 --> 01:01:23.390
and I would actually copy
the words, these letters,

01:01:23.390 --> 01:01:26.150
and then I would ask
him, what is this?

01:01:26.150 --> 01:01:28.860
And he would tell me.

01:01:28.860 --> 01:01:32.130
My father then went on
to say something else.

01:01:32.130 --> 01:01:34.250
He said, you know,
before the age of --

01:01:34.250 --> 01:01:40.460
even before the age of four, she
always loved to draw pictures

01:01:40.460 --> 01:01:43.010
and tell stories about them.

01:01:43.010 --> 01:01:48.590
And she said she had
an amazing imagination.

01:01:48.590 --> 01:01:52.950
And I have there my confirmation
that that test and what

01:01:52.950 --> 01:01:56.410
that woman had found
was indeed the reason

01:01:56.410 --> 01:01:57.880
that I became a writer.

01:01:57.880 --> 01:02:01.510
I did one more thing in
my search for the answer

01:02:01.510 --> 01:02:05.650
to my self-esteem and
why I became a writer.

01:02:05.650 --> 01:02:07.250
I found Ms. Durkin.

01:02:07.250 --> 01:02:12.240
I went searching for months
and I finally found a number

01:02:12.240 --> 01:02:14.690
and she was still alive.

01:02:14.690 --> 01:02:16.340
She didn't remember me.

01:02:16.340 --> 01:02:19.700
I said, I was the first
study, your landmark --

01:02:19.700 --> 01:02:22.200
she said, I had so many
children I worked with.

01:02:22.200 --> 01:02:25.480
I told her what my
parents had said.

01:02:25.480 --> 01:02:27.150
She said, that was
very wrong of them.

01:02:27.150 --> 01:02:30.870
It had nothing to do with
what you would become.

01:02:30.870 --> 01:02:34.670
And I said, I just want to
tell you, I became a writer.

01:02:34.670 --> 01:02:36.320
And she said, of course you did.

01:02:36.320 --> 01:02:38.270
You loved to read.

01:02:38.270 --> 01:02:40.110
That's why you became a writer.

01:02:40.110 --> 01:02:45.090
So I thank you, I thank
the library for providing

01:02:45.090 --> 01:02:49.670
to kids the books they need,
because they love to read.

01:03:02.110 --> 01:03:03.520
[Applause] Announcer:
Ladies and gentlemen,

01:03:03.520 --> 01:03:06.890
please welcome the
Library of Congress Prize

01:03:06.890 --> 01:03:09.280
for American Fiction
winner, Annie Proulx.

01:03:09.280 --> 01:03:27.960
[Applause] A. Proulx: I'm hoping
I don't go into a coughing fit.

01:03:35.370 --> 01:03:42.220
I live in the Pacific northwest
and we have been inundated

01:03:42.220 --> 01:03:44.720
with smoke from British
Columbia,

01:03:44.720 --> 01:03:48.610
which seems to be burning
up its forests this summer.

01:03:48.610 --> 01:03:56.310
I'm a little uneasy standing
here because I do not think

01:03:56.310 --> 01:03:59.980
of myself as a real writer.

01:03:59.980 --> 01:04:06.270
What I am and what I have been
for most of my life is a reader.

01:04:06.270 --> 01:04:09.290
For me books are everything.

01:04:09.290 --> 01:04:13.770
I learned to read by
osmosis around age 4.

01:04:13.770 --> 01:04:16.960
My mother read picture
books to me from infancy,

01:04:16.960 --> 01:04:20.080
and after a while I recognized
the letters on the page

01:04:20.080 --> 01:04:24.580
as forming words that could be
understood by looking at them,

01:04:24.580 --> 01:04:28.880
as well as speaking
or hearing them.

01:04:28.880 --> 01:04:32.210
In the extended family, I
was the one who liked to read

01:04:32.210 --> 01:04:35.720
and well-meaning relatives
blissfully ignorant

01:04:35.720 --> 01:04:40.640
of literary discrimination
gave me books of all kinds.

01:04:40.640 --> 01:04:44.420
A first edition of Uncle
Tom's Cabin inscribed

01:04:44.420 --> 01:04:47.480
as a Christmas gift
for Daisy Crowell,

01:04:47.480 --> 01:04:50.710
one of my great grandmother's
sisters.

01:04:50.710 --> 01:04:56.100
Another gift was my Aunt
Pug's college psychology text.

01:04:56.100 --> 01:04:57.400
[ Laughter ]

01:04:57.400 --> 01:05:00.220
It had a page of
about 10 photographs

01:05:00.220 --> 01:05:03.640
of facial expressions
indicating various emotions

01:05:03.640 --> 01:05:06.150
as anger and fear.

01:05:06.150 --> 01:05:10.370
Around the time I entered
first grade my mother took me

01:05:10.370 --> 01:05:14.390
to the local library in
Druid City Connecticut.

01:05:14.390 --> 01:05:19.040
I understood here was an
endless supply of books,

01:05:19.040 --> 01:05:24.710
and I could take them home,
my life became immensely rich.

01:05:24.710 --> 01:05:26.530
Katherine Elizabeth Docks,

01:05:26.530 --> 01:05:30.450
books about early human
awakened a lifetime interest

01:05:30.450 --> 01:05:32.460
in prehistory.

01:05:32.460 --> 01:05:37.860
Howard V. Brown illustrations
inoculated my mind with images

01:05:37.860 --> 01:05:40.070
of cave bears, saber
tooth tigers,

01:05:40.070 --> 01:05:44.020
wild-eyed people wearing animal
skins and perched in trees

01:05:44.020 --> 01:05:46.250
above flooding rivers.

01:05:46.250 --> 01:05:51.760
The first adult book I read
was Jack London's "before Adam.

01:05:51.760 --> 01:05:56.220
" Adult sexuality was strong
stuff for an eight-year-old.

01:05:56.220 --> 01:05:59.530
[ Laughter ]

01:05:59.530 --> 01:06:01.820
As much as words and
stories meant to me,

01:06:01.820 --> 01:06:05.610
book illustrations were
unfor getably important.

01:06:05.610 --> 01:06:07.980
My vision of European
forests was formed

01:06:07.980 --> 01:06:10.820
by Arthur Rackham's
fairy tail illustrations

01:06:10.820 --> 01:06:15.210
of twisted choking trees
until I had occasion

01:06:15.210 --> 01:06:20.240
to visit the ancient
forest in Poland this year.

01:06:20.240 --> 01:06:24.190
I happily mix children
and adult books.

01:06:24.190 --> 01:06:27.060
In my early teens I
chose non-fiction books

01:06:27.060 --> 01:06:30.040
by the color of binds.

01:06:30.040 --> 01:06:37.130
I had read "mutiny on the
bounty" with great pleasure.

01:06:37.130 --> 01:06:40.470
I subconsciously thought beige
buckram books would be the

01:06:40.470 --> 01:06:43.360
most interesting.

01:06:43.360 --> 01:06:49.380
But Dr. Harold Kratz
autobiographical account

01:06:49.380 --> 01:06:56.360
of his life as a medical student
entitled Campus Shadows bound

01:06:56.360 --> 01:07:01.060
in midnight blue
disamused me of the notion.

01:07:01.060 --> 01:07:04.240
In high school I started
accumulating my own library

01:07:04.240 --> 01:07:07.230
with many modern
library editions.

01:07:07.230 --> 01:07:11.110
The poems of William Blake
joined the short stories

01:07:11.110 --> 01:07:15.680
of Fitzgerald, Stevenson,
Melville, Thoreau,

01:07:15.680 --> 01:07:19.950
Ernest Hemingway and I
was found of recallings.

01:07:19.950 --> 01:07:22.960
Years later I could
only think what a thrill

01:07:22.960 --> 01:07:27.200
if I had discovered Bartam's
travels at that time.

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:29.670
Novels captivated
with people different

01:07:29.670 --> 01:07:31.140
from my small New England world.

01:07:31.140 --> 01:07:37.770
More and more I was attracted
to books about distant places

01:07:37.770 --> 01:07:42.910
and began to move away
from fiction to exploration

01:07:42.910 --> 01:07:51.010
and see stories, mountain
climbing, wilderness travel,

01:07:51.010 --> 01:07:55.170
sermons, oratory, and history.

01:07:55.170 --> 01:08:03.920
My love for history started then
and I later found the approach

01:08:03.920 --> 01:08:06.010
to the past agreeable.

01:08:06.010 --> 01:08:10.710
I was anxious to get to high
school so I could learn Latin.

01:08:10.710 --> 01:08:14.440
Those were the days when
they still taught Latin

01:08:14.440 --> 01:08:15.740
in high school.

01:08:15.740 --> 01:08:19.480
But I found it difficult

01:08:19.480 --> 01:08:25.640
and spent many frustrated
hours puzzling

01:08:25.640 --> 01:08:28.300
over Cicero's sentences.

01:08:28.300 --> 01:08:32.900
I see now good training
for sentence construction.

01:08:32.900 --> 01:08:37.270
Latin is such a tighten folded
language, it takes yards

01:08:37.270 --> 01:08:42.040
of English words to tease
out the compressed meanings.

01:08:42.040 --> 01:08:43.950
The first foreign writer I read

01:08:43.950 --> 01:08:48.510
in translation was Kafka's
Metaphor followed by others.

01:08:48.510 --> 01:08:54.230
I read also Ladner, Hurst,
Conrad, Aiken, stories rather

01:08:54.230 --> 01:08:58.530
than poems, and Irish
short story collections

01:08:58.530 --> 01:09:00.450
as I could find.

01:09:00.450 --> 01:09:04.520
I was powerfully attracted to
short stories from Katherine

01:09:04.520 --> 01:09:11.830
and porter's Noon Wine
made indelible impression.

01:09:11.830 --> 01:09:21.730
It would take many hours to name
the books I've read in my life,

01:09:21.730 --> 01:09:25.090
but after 50 or so years
of this omnivorous reading,

01:09:25.090 --> 01:09:29.810
I began to sense an invisible
something behind all the stories

01:09:29.810 --> 01:09:31.190
and texts.

01:09:31.190 --> 01:09:34.910
Something I could
not quite grasp.

01:09:34.910 --> 01:09:38.900
After falling into a
particularly beautiful passage

01:09:38.900 --> 01:09:46.830
in anthropologist, I started to
read less for plot and character

01:09:46.830 --> 01:09:50.610
and more for discovering
finally written passages

01:09:50.610 --> 01:09:53.140
and shapely paragraphs.

01:09:53.140 --> 01:09:55.990
I became aware of structure.

01:09:55.990 --> 01:09:58.350
Aware of the human
minds and hands

01:09:58.350 --> 01:10:01.660
that arranged the
words on the page.

01:10:01.660 --> 01:10:03.930
And I came to believe
that fiction

01:10:03.930 --> 01:10:07.760
and especially the short
story could be a way

01:10:07.760 --> 01:10:09.960
for understanding how we fit

01:10:09.960 --> 01:10:14.950
into constantly changing
societies and how the geography

01:10:14.950 --> 01:10:16.970
of where we live, the region

01:10:16.970 --> 01:10:21.570
and culture determine
the arcs of our lives.

01:10:21.570 --> 01:10:26.090
So, 20 odd years or so ago,
I began to work out some

01:10:26.090 --> 01:10:29.750
of these ideas myself.

01:10:29.750 --> 01:10:35.300
Now I'm old, but reading more
than ever, and I am reading now

01:10:35.300 --> 01:10:43.230
about genetics, human and animal
migration s,esturine tides,

01:10:43.230 --> 01:10:49.680
seaweed, filmmakers,
wolves and wildfire.

01:10:49.680 --> 01:10:52.450
Ain't it great?

01:10:52.450 --> 01:10:55.660
